The practical difference between the study of ancient, profane, and modern history amounts to this, that in the former the student’s attention is ‘⁶ confined almost exclusively to two countries, and to a few great writers, whose superior claims to attention are indisputable,” whilst in the latter, “instead of two countries, he finds several systems of countries, any one of which offers a wide field of enquiry,” with a multitude of authorities, con- stituting ‘⁶ a boundless wilderness of historical materials.”—Arnold.
